  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>Pools are one of the most polarising features in a Brisbane property campaign. For some buyers, a pool is non-negotiable: a young family with two children, a household that entertains often, or a buyer relocating from interstate who has rented homes with pools and now expects one. For other buyers, the pool is a tax on lifestyle: an annual cost they would rather not carry, a piece of the backyard they would prefer as lawn, and a compliance and safety obligation they would rather avoid. The financial question for sellers and owner-occupiers is therefore less "is a pool worth it" in the abstract and more "for the buyer pool of my specific home and suburb, what does the pool add or subtract, and what does it cost to operate well in the meantime."</p>

      <p>This article walks through the realistic cost of owning a residential pool in Brisbane, the variables that drive ongoing operating cost, the compliance framework, and the way buyer perception tends to land at sale. The aim is to give sellers a more grounded basis for decisions about pool installation, replacement, removal, or simply resetting expectations about what the pool is worth in their next campaign.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Installation cost: the wide range that real quotes produce</h2>
      <p>Installing a new in-ground pool in Brisbane covers an enormous range, depending on size, shape, construction method, finishes, surrounds, and site conditions. A basic small fibreglass pool with simple paving, single-skim coping, and minimal landscaping might land in the lower tier of pool installations. A larger concrete pool with feature tile, raised spa, glass fencing, in-built lighting and water features, integrated paving, and a substantial landscaping reset around it can cost several multiples of that. Site access is the wild card: a backyard with easy crane or excavator access, a flat shell pad, and uncomplicated services is dramatically cheaper to build into than a tight inner-east block where the only access is through a side path or over the roof. Sellers and owners considering installation should always get at least three quotes from established pool builders who have visited the site in person and produced a written scope. The verbal estimate at a home expo is almost never the final number.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Ongoing operating cost: what a Brisbane pool actually costs to run</h2>
      <p>Once the pool is in, the year-round operating cost has several components. Power for the pump, heater (if installed), and any feature lighting is usually the largest line item, particularly for owners running a heat pump through winter to extend the swim season. Chemicals (chlorine, acid, salt for salt-chlorinated systems, stabiliser, clarifier, algaecide as needed) are the next category. Equipment servicing and consumables (filter media replacement, pump and chlorinator service, cell replacement on salt systems every several years, occasional repairs to handles, lights, and timers) round out the ongoing cost. Owners who use a pool service for a fortnightly visit add a meaningful subscription cost on top, and owners who self-maintain still spend an hour a week on average across the year on water testing, brushing, vacuuming, and skimming. The realistic annual cost for a typical inner-east family pool, properly maintained and heated for the shoulder seasons, runs into the low thousands of dollars and can climb meaningfully from there for larger or feature-heavy installations.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Insurance and council rates implications</h2>
      <p>Home insurance premiums for properties with a pool are typically higher than equivalent properties without one, reflecting the additional liability profile. The increase is rarely the largest line item in pool ownership but it is real and ongoing. Brisbane City Council rates are not directly affected by pool installation, but the value uplift the pool provides (where any) flows through to land valuation and rates over time in a small way. Sellers should treat insurance differential as one of the routine costs of owning a pool, not as a one-off concern.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pool safety compliance: the framework that genuinely matters at sale</h2>
      <p>Queensland operates a pool safety regime that requires regulated pools to have a current pool safety certificate at the point of sale or lease. The certificate is issued by a licensed pool safety inspector who has assessed the pool fence, gate, latching mechanism, pool surrounds, and anything that could be used by a child to climb the barrier. Inner-east sellers regularly find that a pool that was compliant five or ten years ago no longer meets current standards because trees have grown into climbable position, outdoor furniture has been placed too close to the fence, a pet door has been added to a wall adjacent to the pool, or fencing materials have aged. The cost of bringing a pool back to compliance ranges from minor (a new latch, a section of fence panel) to substantial (a replacement glass fence, regrading of the pool surrounds, removal of climbable items at significant cost). Sellers should always book a pool safety inspection well before listing rather than discovering issues at the contract stage. A non-compliant pool is not a contract-breaker in Queensland (the regime allows the buyer to take responsibility for compliance within a defined window post-settlement), but it weakens negotiation position and tends to flow into price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What a pool actually adds at sale: the suburb and buyer pool question</h2>
      <p>The headline question (does a pool add value at sale) is genuinely suburb-specific in Brisbane. In family-oriented inner-east suburbs (Bulimba, Hawthorne, Camp Hill, Norman Park, Carindale), a well-maintained pool on a property of the right size for a family typically does add value, particularly for the upper-end family home segment where the buyer pool actively wants a pool. In the same suburbs, a small pool on a tight block that has compromised the usable garden, or a tired older pool that visibly needs work, often adds nothing or actively detracts from value because buyers price in the cost of replacement or removal. In suburbs where the buyer pool is more weighted to downsizers, professional couples, or first home buyers (Coorparoo and parts of Camp Hill at certain price points, Greenslopes, parts of Morningside), a pool more often reads as a maintenance and compliance burden than as a selling feature. The right read is local and depends on the specific property and price band, not on a general rule.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Pool condition matters more than pool existence</h2>
      <p>Across the inner east, the gap between a well-kept pool and a tired one is often larger at sale than the gap between having a pool and not having one. A pool that is sparkling at every open home, with clean coping, neat surrounds, working lighting, fresh tile grout, and a well-maintained equipment area, reads as an asset. A pool with cloudy water, stained surfaces, cracked tiles, an obviously aged pump, sagging fence panels, and overgrown surrounds reads as a future cost the buyer will have to absorb. Pre-listing investment in pool presentation (a chemical reset by a pool service, replacement of any visibly aged equipment, a minor tile and grout refresh, a tidy of the surrounds and equipment area) almost always pays for itself in the way buyers respond to the property at open homes. This is one of the highest-yield small expenses sellers can make in the weeks before listing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Should you remove a pool before selling?</h2>
      <p>Pool removal is a question that comes up periodically, particularly with smaller older fibreglass pools on tight blocks where the pool has effectively swallowed the usable garden. The economics of removal are not trivial. Demolition, removal of the shell, backfilling, soil compaction, and turf or paving over the slab footprint can run into the tens of thousands of dollars, and the works typically take a few weeks to complete. The case for removal is usually situational rather than financial: a pool that is genuinely compromising the usable yard, in a suburb where the buyer pool does not want a pool, on a property where the marketing story is much stronger as a family home with a usable garden than as a home with a small pool. For most Brisbane properties, removal is not the right answer. For a small subset of properties where the pool is a genuine drag on appeal, it can be. This is a question to walk through with an agent who knows the local buyer pool well.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Heat pumps, solar heating, and seasonal swim window</h2>
      <p>Brisbane's climate gives a residential pool a meaningfully longer swim season than southern capitals, but most Brisbane pools are still effectively cold for at least three to four months of the year unless heated. Solar heating (panels on the roof through which pool water is circulated) and electric heat pumps are the two common options, with heat pumps the more expensive to install and run but more reliable across cooler weeks and overcast stretches. The decision to add heating depends on how the household actually uses the pool, the orientation and roof area for solar, and the budget for ongoing electricity. From a sale perspective, working heating is a feature that can be highlighted in marketing; non-functional or visibly aged heating equipment is a question buyers will raise.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">A simple decision framework for owners</h2>
      <p>For owners weighing pool installation, replacement, or significant upgrade ahead of a future sale, the framework is roughly: identify the realistic buyer pool for your suburb and price band, get a candid view from a local agent on whether that buyer pool actively wants a pool, check the realistic installed cost against any uplift the pool would actually add at sale, and factor the ongoing operating cost across the years you would own the home before selling. For most inner-east family homes in the right price band, a well-presented pool is a net positive at sale and a meaningful lifestyle asset in the meantime. For some properties, the same money is better spent on a different upgrade. The right answer depends on the specific property, the suburb, and the household's own use of the space.</p>

